stand today Since scholars began interrogating the meaning of gender and sexuality in society, this field has become essential to the study of sociology. Gender Reckonings aims to map new directions for understanding gender and sexuality within a more pragmatic, dynamic, and socially relevant framework. It shows how gender relations must be understood on a large scale as well as in intimate detail.The contributors return to the basics, questioning how gender patterns change, how we can realize gender equality, and how the structures of gender impact daily life. Gender Reckonings covers not only foundational concepts of gender relations and gender justice, but also explores postcolonial patterns of gender, intersectionality, gender fluidity, transgender practices, neoliberalism, and queer theory. Gender Reckonings combines the insights of gender and sexuality scholars from different generations, fields, and world regions. The editors and contributors are leading social scientists from six continents, and the book gives vivid accounts of the changing politics of gender in different communities.Rich in empirical detail and novel thinking, Gender Reckonings is a lasting resource for students, researchers, activists, policymakers, and everyone concerned with gender justice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jun 2020) 0aGender identity. 0aSex role. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh1 aConnell, Raewyn, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMartin, Patricia Yancey, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMesserschmidt, James W., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMessner, Michael A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479866342423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781479866342.jpg